> Patrick first tasted this dish when arriving in the beautiful hilltop village of Grottaferrata, just south of Rome and asked a local chef to show him the recipe. It's another example of that wonderful Italian ability to let a few fantastic quality ingredients speak for themselves and the addition of parsley gives it a sublime, fresh dimension. Rumour has it the aubergine tastes akin to a type of mushroom, which may explain why it is called 'al funghetto' despite being totally mushroomless!

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees and boil a #pot{} of water for your @new potatoes{1}. Peel and finely dice the @garlic{2%cloves}. Chop the @cherry tomatoes{1} into quarters. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{3}.

Cut your @aubergine{1} in half lengthways and cut each piece in half lengthways again. Remove the spongy white part in the middle and discard (just like the picture left). Slice each strip in half lengthways once more (so you have eight strips in total). Now dice the aubergine.

Cook your potatoes in the boiling water with @salt{1/4%tsp} for around ~{10-15%minutes}, then drain and keep to one side with a lid on.

> Tip: They are done when you can slip a knife through them.

Place your hand flat on top of the @British chicken breasts{2} and slice through the middle to open it up like a book. Repeat for your other chicken breast. Once you have 'butterflied' the chicken breasts, put them on a #baking tray{}. Coat each breast in @olive oil{1%tsp} and a @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Grate over some @lemon{1/2}(zested) and @lemon juice{1%tsp} and cover the #tray{} with #tin foil{} (if you have some).

Pop your chicken breasts on the top shelf of the oven and cook for around ~{15%minutes}, until they are no longer pink in the middle.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add your aubergine and cook for ~{5%minutes}, then add @chilli flakes{1/4%tsp}(pinched) (or more if you're brave!) and the garlic and cook for a further ~{1%minute}. Add the cherry tomatoes and continue to cook them for about ~{10%minutes} until they are nice and soft. Add @water{1%tbsp} every few mins to stop them drying out.

Lastly, stir your chopped parsley and the potatoes through the aubergine mixture and serve your chicken on top. Buon appetito!